      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Mideast Violence Strikes a Raw Nerve</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Katcoff letter, replying to Rami G Khouri's Oct 10 Op-Ed article, says Ariel Sharon can do what he did on Haram al Sharif because in a democracy like Israel, Prime Min Ehud Barak cannot silence him; says this is to Israel's credit</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Israel's Deadly Errors'' (Op-Ed, Oct. 10):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Israel's Deadly Errors'' (Op-Ed, Oct. 10):</p>
        <p>Rami G. Khouri says Ariel Sharon's visit to Haram al Sharif, or Noble Sanctuary, was ''taken by all Arabs and Muslims as a direct, predatory Israeli threat.'' This attitude illustrates the difference between democracy and despotism.</p>
        <p>In a democracy, one of the consequences of freedom of speech is that people we despise often show up at inconvenient times and places and express themselves in irritating ways that we have to tolerate. In a dictatorship, the insecurity of those who rule is reflected in the need for maintaining a sanitized environment where dissenting opinions are suppressed.</p>
        <p>It should be a source of inspiration to the Arabs that Israel can have such a liberal prime minister who will allow someone from his political opposition to exercise his civil rights.</p>
        <p>DAVID KATCOFF  Jericho, Vt., Oct. 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
